# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fhir-health
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] An **electronic health record** (**EHR**) is the systematized collection of electronically stored patient and population health information in a digital format.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] These records can be shared across different health care settings.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Records are shared through network-connected, enterprise-wide information systems or other information networks and exchanges.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] EHRs may include a range of data, including demographics, medical history, medication and allergies, immunization status, laboratory test results, radiology images, vital signs, personal statistics like age and weight, and billing information.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] For several decades, EHRs have been touted as key to increasing quality of care.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] EHR combines all patients' demographics into a large pool, which assists providers in the creation of "new treatments or innovation in healthcare delivery" to improve quality outcomes in healthcare.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Combining multiple types of clinical data within electronic health records has enabled clinicians to identify and stratify patients with chronic conditions.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] EHR systems may also support improvements in quality of care through the use of data and analytics to help prevent hospitalizations among high-risk patients.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] EHR systems are designed to store data accurately and to capture a patient's state across time.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] It eliminates the need to track down a patient's previous paper medical records and assists in ensuring data is up-to-date, accurate, and legible.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] It also allows open communication between the patient and the provider while providing "privacy and security." EHR is cost-efficient, decreases the risk of lost paperwork, and can reduce risk of data replication as there is only one modifiable file, which means the file is more likely up to date.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Due to the digital information being searchable and in a single file, EMRs (electronic medical records) are more effective when extracting medical data to examine possible trends and long-term changes in a patient.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The widespread adoption of EHRs and EMRs may also facilitate population-based studies of medical records.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The terms **electronic health record** (**EHR**), **electronic patient record** (**EPR**), and **electronic medical record** (**EMR**) have often been used interchangeably, but "subtle" differences exist.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The EHR is a more longitudinal collection of the electronic health information of individual patients or populations.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The EMR, in contrast, is the patient record created by providers for specific encounters in hospitals and ambulatory environments and can serve as a data source for an EHR.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] EMRs are essentially digital versions of the paper documents used in a clinician's office, typically functioning as an internal system within a practice.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] An EMR includes the medical and treatment history of patients treated by that specific practice.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] In contrast, a personal health record (PHR) is an electronic application for recording individual medical data that the individual patient controls and may make available to health providers.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] While there is ongoing debate regarding the advantages of electronic health records compared with paper records, the research literature presents a more nuanced view of their benefits and limitations.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Proponents of EHR note that these systems can substantially reduce such burdens, for example cutting time spent on insurance eligibility tasks by more than 80%.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] But along with increased convenience, transparency, portability, and accessibility, there is also an increased risk that sensitive information may be accessed by unauthorized persons or unscrupulous users (versus paper medical records).
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] This is acknowledged by the increased security requirements for electronic medical records included in the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) and by large-scale breaches in confidential records reported by EMR users.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Meanwhile, handwritten paper medical records may be poorly legible, which can contribute to medical errors.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Pre-printed forms, standardization of abbreviations, and standards for penmanship were encouraged to improve the reliability of paper medical records.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] An example of possible medical errors is the administration of medication.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Medication is an intervention that can turn a person's status from stable to unstable very quickly.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] With paper documentation it is very easy to not properly document the administration of medication, the time given, or errors such as giving the "wrong drug, dose, form, or not checking for allergies," and could affect the patient negatively.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] It has been reported that these errors have been reduced by "55-83%" because records are now online and require specific steps to avoid these errors.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Electronic records may help with the standardization of forms, terminology, and data input.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Digitization of forms facilitates the collection of data for epidemiology and clinical studies.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] However, standardization may create challenges for local practice.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Overall, those with EMRs that have automated notes and records, order entry, and clinical decision support had fewer complications, lower mortality rates, and lower costs.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] EMRs can be continuously updated (within certain legal limitations: see below).
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] If the ability to exchange records between different EMR systems were perfected ("interoperability"), it would facilitate the coordination of health care delivery in non-affiliated health care facilities.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] In addition, data from an electronic system can be used anonymously for statistical reporting in matters such as quality improvement, resource management, and public health communicable disease surveillance.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] However, it is difficult to remove data from its context.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Providing patients with information is central to patient-centered health care and has been shown to positively affect health outcomes.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Providing patients access to their health records, including medical histories and test results via an EHR, is a legal right in some parts of the world.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] There is evidence that patient access may help patients understand their conditions and actively involve them in their management.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] For example, granting people who have type 2 diabetes access to their electronic health records may help these people to reduce their blood sugar levels.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Challenges with sharing the electronic health record with patients include a risk of increased confusion or anxiety if a person does not understand or cannot contextualize the testing results.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] In addition, many EHRs are not designed for people of all educational levels and do not consider the needs of those with a lower level of education or those who are not fluent in the language.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Accessing the EHR requires a level of proficiency with electronic devices, which adds to a disparity for those without access or for those who have a mental or physical illness that restricts their access to the electronic system.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Electronic medical records could also be studied to quantify disease burdens – such as the number of deaths from antimicrobial resistance – or help identify causes of, factors of, links between, and contributors to diseases, especially when combined with genome-wide association studies.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Ambulance services in Australia, the United States, and the United Kingdom have introduced EMR systems.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] EMS Encounters in the United States are recorded using various platforms and vendors in compliance with the NEMSIS (National EMS Information System) standard.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Using an EMR to read and write a patient's record is not only possible through a workstation but, depending on the type of system and health care settings, may also be possible through mobile devices that are handwriting capable, such as tablets and smartphones.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Electronic medical records may include access to personal health records (PHR) which makes individual notes from an EMR readily visible and accessible to consumers.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Some EMR systems automatically monitor clinical events by analyzing patient data from an electronic health record to predict, detect, and potentially prevent adverse events.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] This can include discharge/transfer orders, pharmacy orders, radiology results, laboratory results, and any other data from ancillary services or provider notes.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] This type of event monitoring has been implemented using the Louisiana Public Health Information Exchange, which links statewide public health with electronic medical records.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] This system alerted medical providers when a patient with HIV/AIDS had not received care in over twelve months.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] This system greatly reduced the number of missed critical opportunities.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Within a meta-narrative systematic review of research in the field, various different philosophical approaches to the EHR exist.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The health information systems literature has seen the EHR as a container holding information about the patient and a tool for aggregating clinical data for secondary uses (billing, audit, etc.).
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] However, other research traditions see the EHR as a contextualized artifact within a socio-technical system.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] For example, actor-network theory would see the EHR as an actant in a network, and research in computer-supported cooperative work (CSCW) sees the EHR as a tool supporting particular work.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Several possible advantages to EHRs over paper records have been proposed, but there is debate about the degree to which these are achieved in practice.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Several studies call into question whether EHRs improve the quality of care.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] One 2011 study in diabetes care, published in the *New England Journal of Medicine*, found evidence that practices with EHR provided better quality care.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] EMRs may eventually help improve care coordination.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] An article in a trade journal suggests that since anyone using an EMR can view the patient's full chart, it cuts down on guessing histories and seeing multiple specialists, smooths transitions between care settings, and may allow better care in emergency situations.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] EHRs may also improve prevention by providing doctors and patients better access to test results, identifying missing patient information, and offering evidence-based recommendations for preventive services.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] At one time, the steep price and provider uncertainty regarding the value they might derive from adoption (in terms of return on investment) lead to significant resistance to EHR adoption.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] As late as 2010, doctors complained that such systems were too cumbersome, eating up time otherwise spent with patients.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Congressional Budget Office concluded that the cost savings may occur only in large integrated institutions like Kaiser Permanente and not in small physician offices.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] "Office-based physicians in particular may see no benefit if they purchase such a product—and may even suffer financial harm.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Even though the use of health IT could generate cost savings for the health system at large that might offset the EHR's cost, many physicians might not be able to reduce their office expenses or increase their revenue sufficiently to pay for it.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] For example, the use of health IT could reduce the number of duplicated diagnostic tests.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Doubts about cost saving from EHRs continued through the early 2000s, raised by researchers at Harvard University, the Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania, Stanford University, and others.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] At this time only around 10% of U.S. hospitals and 20% of private practices used EHR systems.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] By 2015, with the rise of cloud-based EHR platforms, this had changed drastically, with 96% of all hospitals and nearly 80% of office-based physicians implementing an EHR system.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The implementation of EMR can potentially decrease the identification time of patients upon hospital admission.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Research by the Annals of Internal Medicine showed that since the adoption of EMR, a relative decrease in time by 65% has been recorded (from 130 to 46 hours).
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The Healthcare Information and Management Systems Society, a very large U.S. healthcare IT industry trade group, observed in 2009 that EHR adoption rates "have been slower than expected in the United States, especially compared to other industry sectors and other developed countries.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Aside from initial costs and lost productivity during EMR implementation, one key reason is lack of efficiency and usability of EMRs currently available." The U.S.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] National Institute of Standards and Technology of the Department of Commerce studied usability in 2011 and lists a number of specific issues that have been reported by health care workers.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The U.S. military's EHR, AHLTA, was reported to have significant usability issues.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] It was observed that the efforts to improve EHR usability should be placed in the context of physician-patient communication.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] However, physicians are embracing mobile technologies such as smartphones and tablets at a rapid pace.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] According to a 2012 survey by *Physicians Practice*, 62.6 percent of respondents (1,369 physicians, practice managers, and other healthcare providers) say they use mobile devices in the performance of their job.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Mobile devices are increasingly able to sync up with electronic health record systems, allowing physicians to access patient records from remote locations.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Most devices are extensions of desktop EHR systems, using a variety of software to communicate and access files remotely.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The advantages of instant access to patient records at any time and place are clear, but raise security concerns.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] As mobile systems become more prevalent, practices will need comprehensive policies that govern security measures and patient privacy regulations.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Other advanced computational techniques allow EHRs to be evaluated at a much quicker rate.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Natural language processing is increasingly used to search EMRs, especially through searching and analyzing notes and text that would otherwise be inaccessible for study when seeking to improve care.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] One study found that several machine learning methods could be used to predict the rate of a patient's mortality with moderate success, with the most successful approach including using a combination of a convolutional neural network and a heterogenous graph model.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] When a health facility has documented its workflow and chosen its software solution, it must consider the hardware and supporting device infrastructure for the end users.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Staff and patients must engage with various devices throughout a patient's stay and charting workflow.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Computers, laptops, all-in-one computers, tablets, mouse, keyboards and monitors are all hardware devices that may be utilized.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Other considerations include supporting work surfaces and equipment, wall desks or articulating arms for end users to work on.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Another important factor is how all these devices will be physically secured and how they will be charged so that staff can always utilize them for EHR charting when needed.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The success of eHealth interventions largely depends on the adopter's ability to fully understand workflow and anticipate potential clinical processes prior to implementations.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Failure to do so can create costly and time-consuming interruptions to service delivery.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Per empirical research in social informatics, information and communications technology (ICT) use can lead to both intended and unintended consequences.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] A 2008 Sentinel Event Alert from the U.S.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Technology-related adverse events can be associated with all components of a comprehensive technology system and may involve errors of either commission or omission.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The British National Health Service (NHS) reports specific examples of potential and actual EHR-caused unintended consequences in its 2009 document on the management of clinical risk relating to the deployment and use of health software.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] A 2010 Board Position Paper by the American Medical Informatics Association (AMIA) contains recommendations on EHR-related patient safety, transparency, ethics education for purchasers and users, adoption of best practices, and re-examination of regulation of electronic health applications.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Beyond concrete issues such as conflicts of interest and privacy concerns, questions have been raised about how the physician-patient relationship would be affected by an electronic intermediary.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] During the implementation phase, cognitive workload for healthcare professionals may be significantly increased as they familiarize themselves with a new system.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] EHRs are almost invariably detrimental to physician productivity, whether the data is entered during the encounter or sometime thereafter.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] It is possible for an EHR to increase physician productivity.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] It can provide a fast and intuitive interface for viewing and understanding patient clinical data and minimizing the number of clinically irrelevant questions.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The other way to mitigate the detriment to physician productivity is to hire scribes to work alongside medical practitioners, which is almost never financially viable.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] In the United States, Great Britain, and Germany, the concept of a national centralized server model of healthcare data has been poorly received.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Concerns include issues of privacy and security.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] In the European Union (EU), a new directly binding instrument, a regulation of the European Parliament and of the council, was passed in 2016 to go into effect in 2018 to protect the processing of personal data, including that for purposes of health care, the General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] These threats can either be internal, external, intentional, or unintentional.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Health information systems professionals consider these particular threats when discussing ways to protect patients' health information.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] It has been found that there is a lack of security awareness among health care professionals in countries such as Spain.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) has developed a framework to mitigate the harm of these threats that is comprehensive but not so specific as to limit the options of healthcare professionals who may have access to different technology.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] With the increase of clinical notes being shared electronically due to the 21st Century Cures Act, an increase in sensitive terms used across the records of all patients, including minors, are increasingly shared amongst care teams, complicating efforts to maintain privacy.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Personal Information Protection and Electronic Documents Act (PIPEDA) was given Royal Assent in Canada on 13 April 2000 to establish rules on the use, disclosure, and collection of personal information.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The personal information includes both non-digital and electronic forms.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] In 2002, PIPEDA extended to the health sector in Stage 2 of the law's implementation.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] There are four provinces where this law does not apply because their privacy laws were considered similar to PIPEDA: Alberta, British Columbia, Ontario, and Quebec.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The COVID-19 pandemic in the United Kingdom led to radical changes.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] NHS Digital and NHSX made changes, said to be only for the duration of the crisis, to the information sharing system GP Connect across England, meaning that patient records are shared across primary care.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Only patients who have specifically opted out are excluded.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Legal liability in all aspects of health care was an increasing problem in the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The surge in the per capita number of attorneys in the USA and changes in the tort system caused an increase in the cost of every aspect of health care, and health care technology was no exception.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Failure or damages caused during installation or utilization of an EHR system has been feared as a threat in lawsuits.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Similarly, the implementation of electronic health records can carry significant legal risks.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Liability is of special concern for small EHR system makers, which may be forced to abandon markets based on the regional liability climate.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Larger EHR providers (or government-sponsored providers of EHRs) are better able to withstand legal challenges.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Electronic documentation of patient visits and data could open physicians to an increased incidence of malpractice suits.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Disabling physician alerts, selecting from dropdown menus, and using templates can encourage physicians to skip a complete review of past patient history and medications and thus miss important data.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Another potential problem is electronic time stamps.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Many physicians are unaware that EHR systems produce an electronic time stamp every time the patient record is updated.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] If a malpractice claim goes to court, the prosecution can request a detailed record of all entries made in a patient's electronic record.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Waiting to chart patient notes until the end of the day and making addendums to records well after the patient visit can be problematic in that this practice could result in less than accurate patient data or indicate possible intent to illegally alter the patient's record.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] In some communities, hospitals attempt to standardize EHR systems by providing discounted versions of the hospital's software to local healthcare providers.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] A challenge to this practice has been raised as being a violation of Stark rules that prohibit hospitals from preferentially assisting community healthcare providers.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] In 2006, however, exceptions to the Stark rule were enacted to allow hospitals to furnish software and training to community providers, mostly removing this legal obstacle.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] In cross-border use cases of EHR implementations, the additional issue of legal interoperability arises.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Different countries may have diverging legal requirements for the content or usage of electronic health records, which can require radical changes to the technical makeup of the EHR implementation in question, especially when fundamental legal incompatibilities are involved.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Exploring these issues is, therefore, often necessary when implementing cross-border EHR solutions.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The United Nations World Health Organization (WHO) administration intentionally does not contribute to an internationally standardized view of medical records nor to personal health records.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] However, the WHO contributes to minimum requirements definitions for developing countries.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The United Nations-accredited standardization body International Organization for Standardization (ISO) however has reviewed and adopted certain standards in the scope of the HL7 platform for health care informatics.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Respective standards are available with ISO/HL7 10781:2009 Electronic Health Record-System Functional Model, Release 1.1 and subsequent set of detailing standards.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The majority of the countries in Europe have made a strategy for the development and implementation of electronic health record systems.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] This would mean greater access to health records by numerous stakeholders, even from countries with lower levels of privacy protection.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The idea of a centralized electronic health record system was poorly received by the public who are wary that governments may use of the system beyond its intended purpose.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] There is also the risk for privacy breaches that could allow sensitive health care information to fall into the wrong hands.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Some countries have enacted laws requiring safeguards to be put in place to protect the security and confidentiality of medical information.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] These safeguards add protection for records that are shared electronically and give patients some important rights to monitor their medical records and receive notification for loss and unauthorized acquisition of health information.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The United States and the EU have imposed mandatory medical data breach notifications.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Researchers noted that extreme market concentration in health information technology created systemic cybersecurity and national security risks, as the compromise of a single entity could affect access to health records for a significant portion of the population.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The purpose of a personal data breach notification is to protect individuals so that they can take all the necessary actions to limit the undesirable effects of the breach and to motivate the organization to improve the security of the infrastructure to protect the confidentiality of the data.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] U.S. law requires the entities to inform the individuals in the event of a breach while the EU Directive currently requires breach notification only when the breach is likely to adversely affect the privacy of the individual.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Personal health data is valuable to individuals and it is therefore difficult to assess whether a breach will cause reputational or financial harm or adversely affect one's privacy.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The breach notification law in the EU provides better privacy safeguards with fewer exemptions, unlike the US law, which exempts unintentional acquisition, access, or use of protected health information and inadvertent disclosure under a good faith belief.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The U.S. federal government has issued new rules of electronic health records.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] A common data model (CDM) is a specification that describes how data from multiple sources (e.g., multiple EHR systems) can be combined.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Many CDMs use a relational model (e.g., the OMOP CDM).
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] A relational CDM defines names of tables and table columns and restricts what values are valid.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Each health care environment functions differently, often in significant ways.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] It is difficult to create a "one-size-fits-all" EHR system.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Many first-generation EHRs were designed to fit the needs of primary care physicians, leaving certain specialties significantly less satisfied with their EHR system.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] An ideal EHR system will have record standardization but also interfaces that can be customized to each provider environment.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Modularity in an EHR system facilitates this.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Many EHR companies employ vendors to provide customization, which can often be done so that a physician's input interface closely mimics previously utilized paper forms.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Providers have reported negative effects in communication, increased overtime, and missing records when a non-customized EMR system was utilized.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Customizing the software when released yields the highest benefits because it is adapted for the users and tailored to workflows specific to the institution.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] However, customization can have its disadvantages.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Implementing a customized system may incur higher initial costs, as more time must be spent by both the implementation team and the healthcare provider to understand the workflow needs.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Development and maintenance of these interfaces and customizations can also lead to higher software implementation and maintenance costs.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] An important consideration when developing electronic health records is to plan for the long-term preservation and storage of these records.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The field will need to come to a consensus on the length of time to store EHRs, methods to ensure the future accessibility and compatibility of archived data with yet-to-be-developed retrieval systems, and how to ensure the physical and virtual security of the archives.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Additionally, considerations about the long-term storage of electronic health records are complicated by the possibility that the records might one day be used longitudinally and integrated across sites of care.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Records have the potential to be created, used, edited, and viewed by multiple independent entities.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] These entities include, but are not limited to, primary care physicians, hospitals, insurance companies, and patients.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The required length of storage of an individual electronic health record will depend on national and state regulations, which are subject to change over time.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Ruotsalainen and Manning have found that the typical preservation time of patient data varies between 20 and 100 years.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] In one example of how an EHR archive might function, their research "describes a co-operative trusted notary archive (TNA) which receives health data from different EHR-systems, stores data together with associated meta-information for long periods and distributes EHR-data objects.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] In addition to the TNA archive described by Ruotsalainen and Manning, other combinations of EHR systems and archive systems are possible.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Again, overall requirements for the design and security of the system and its archive will vary and must function under ethical and legal principles specific to the time and place.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] While it is currently unknown precisely how long EHRs will be preserved, it is certain that length of time will exceed the average shelf-life of paper records.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The evolution of technology is such that the programs and systems used to input information will likely not be available to a user who desires to examine archived data.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] One proposed solution to the challenge of long-term accessibility and usability of data by future systems is to standardize information fields in a time-invariant way, such as with XML language.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Olhede and Peterson report that "the basic XML-format has undergone preliminary testing in Europe by a Spri project and been found suitable for EU purposes.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] When care is provided at two different facilities, it may be difficult to update records at both locations in a coordinated fashion.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Two models have been used to satisfy this problem: a centralized data server solution and a peer-to-peer file synchronization program (as has been developed for other peer-to-peer networks).
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] However, synchronization programs for distributed storage models are only useful once record standardization has occurred.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Merging of already existing public health care databases is a common software challenge.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The ability of electronic health record systems to provide this function is a key benefit and can improve health care delivery.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The sharing of patient information between health care organizations and IT systems is changing from a "point to point" model to a "many to many" one.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The European Commission is supporting moves to facilitate cross-border interoperability of e-health systems and to remove potential legal hurdles.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] To allow for global shared workflow, studies will be locked when they are being read and then unlocked and updated once reading is complete.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] This enables Radiologists to serve multiple health care facilities and read and report across large geographical areas, thus balancing workloads.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The biggest challenges will relate to interoperability and legal clarity.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] In some countries, it is almost forbidden to practice teleradiology.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The variety of languages spoken is a problem, and multilingual reporting templates for all anatomical regions are not yet available.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] However, the market for e-health and teleradiology is evolving more rapidly than any laws or regulations.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] In 2011, Moscow's government launched a major project known as UMIAS as part of its electronic healthcare initiative.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] UMIAS - the Unified Medical Information and Analytical System - connects more than 660 clinics and over 23,600 medical practitioners in Moscow.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] UMIAS covers 9.5 million patients, contains more than 359 million patient records, and supports more than 500,000 different transactions daily.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Approximately 700,000 Muscovites use remote links to make appointments every week.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The European Commission wants to boost the digital economy by enabling all Europeans to have access to online medical records anywhere in Europe.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] With the new European Health Data Space (EHDS) Regulation, steps are being taken toward a centralized European health record system.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] However, the concept of a centralized supranational central server raises concern about storing electronic medical records in a central location.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The privacy threat posed by a supranational network is a key concern.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] The Lloyd George envelope digitisation project aims to have all paper copies of all historic patient data transferred onto computer systems.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] As part of the rollout, new patients will no longer be given a transit label to register when moving practices.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Lyniate was selected to provide data integration technologies for Health and Social Care (Northern Ireland) in 2022.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Epic Systems will supply integrated electronic health records with a single digital record for every citizen.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Lyniate Rhapsody, already used in 79 NHS Trusts, will be used to integrate the multiple health and social care systems.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] In UK veterinary practice, the replacement of paper recording systems with electronic methods of storing animal patient information escalated from the 1980s, and the majority of clinics now use electronic medical records.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] In a sample of 129 veterinary practices, 89% used a Practice Management System (PMS) for data recording.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] There are more than ten PMS providers currently in the UK.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Collecting data directly from PMSs for epidemiological analysis abolishes the need for veterinarians to manually submit individual reports per animal visit and therefore increases the reporting rate.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] A letter published in Communications of the ACM describes the concept of generating synthetic patient populations and proposes a variation of the Turing test to assess the difference between synthetic and real patients.
[src:fhir-health/electronic-health-record] Further, the letter states: "Before synthetic patient identities become a public health problem, the legitimate EHR market might benefit from applying Turing Test-like techniques to ensure greater data reliability and diagnostic value.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] The **Fast Healthcare Interoperability Resources** (**FHIR**, /faɪər/, like *fire*) is a technical standard by HL7 International for health information exchange.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] It is designed for a wide range of settings and with different health care information systems.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] The standard describes data formats and elements (known as "resources") and an API (application programming interface) for exchanging electronic health records (EHR).
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] FHIR builds on previous data format standards from HL7, like HL7 version 2.x and HL7 version 3.x.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] But it is easier to implement because it uses a modern web-based suite of API technology, including a REST protocol, and a choice of JSON, XML or RDF for data representation.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] FHIR provides an alternative to document-centric approaches by directly exposing discrete data elements as services.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] For example, basic elements of healthcare like patients, admissions, diagnostic reports and medications can each be retrieved and manipulated via their own resource URLs.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] FHIR is organized by resources (e.g., patient, observation).
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] Such resources can be specified further by defining FHIR profiles (for example, binding to a specific terminology).
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] A collection of profiles can be published as an implementation guide (IG), such as The U.S.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] The ONC anticipates finalizing USCDI v4 in July 2023.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] Because FHIR is implemented on top of HTTPS, FHIR resources can be retrieved and parsed by analytics platforms for real-time data gathering.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] In this concept, healthcare organizations would be able to gather real-time data from specified resource models.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] FHIR resources can be streamed to a data store where they can be correlated with other informatics data.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] Potential use cases include epidemic tracking, prescription drug fraud, adverse drug interaction warnings, and the reduction of emergency room wait times.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] In 2025, an international working group with contributors from CSIRO, Google, Microsoft Research, Harvard Medical School, and Health Samurai published the SQL on FHIR specification in *npj Digital Medicine*.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] The specification defines an implementation-agnostic method for producing tabular views of FHIR resources using FHIRPath expressions, intended to address performance and complexity issues encountered when querying large FHIR datasets in their native JSON or XML formats.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] The specification was validated by replicating a clinical study using two independent implementations — Pathling, developed by CSIRO, and Aidbox, developed by Health Samurai — over a dataset of approximately 580 million FHIR resources, producing identical results across both runners.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] Globally, a number of high-profile players in the health care informatics field are showing interest in and experimenting with FHIR, including CommonWell Health Alliance and SMART (Substitutable Medical Applications, Reusable Technologies).
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] Open source implementations of FHIR data structures, servers, clients and tools include reference implementations from HL7 in a variety of languages, SMART on FHIR, HAPI-FHIR in Java, and many others (see reference).
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] A variety of applications were demonstrated at the FHIR Applications Roundtable in July 2016.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] The Sync for Science (S4S) profile builds on FHIR to help medical research studies ask for (and if approved by the patient, receive) patient-level electronic health record data.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] In January, 2018, Apple announced that its iPhone Health App would allow viewing a user's FHIR-compliant medical records when providers choose to make them available.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] Johns Hopkins Medicine, Cedars-Sinai, Penn Medicine, NYU-Langone Medical Center, Dignity Health and other large hospital systems participated at launch.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] Health IT Policy and the Health IT Standards committees endorsed recommendations for more public (open) APIs.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] JASON task force report on "A Robust Health Data Infrastructure" says that FHIR is currently the best candidate API approach, and that such APIs should be part of stage 3 of the "meaningful use" criteria of the U.S.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] Health Information Technology for Economic and Clinical Health Act.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] In December 2014, a broad cross-section of US stakeholders committed to the Argonaut Project which will provide acceleration funding and political will to publish FHIR implementation guides and profiles for query/response interoperability and document retrieval by May 2015.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] It would then be possible for medical records systems to migrate from the current practice of exchanging complex Clinical Document Architecture (CDA) documents, and instead exchange sets of simpler, more modular and interoperable FHIR JSON objects.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] The initial goal was to specify two FHIR profiles that are relevant to the Meaningful Use requirements, along with an implementation guide for using OAuth 2.0 for authentication.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] A collaboration agreement with Healthcare Services Platform Consortium (now called Logica) was announced in 2017.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] Experiences with developing medical applications using FHIR to link to existing electronic health record systems clarified some of the benefits and challenges of the approach, and with getting clinicians to use them.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services (CMS) issued their *Interoperability and Patient Access final rule,* (CMS-9115-F), based on the 21st Century Cures Act.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] The rule requires the use of FHIR by a variety of CMS-regulated payers, including Medicare Advantage organizations, state Medicaid programs, and qualified health plans in the Federally Facilitated Marketplace by 2021.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] Specifically, the rule requires FHIR APIs for Patient Access, Provider Directory and Payer-to-Payer exchange.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] Proposed rules from CMS, such as the patient burden and prior authorization proposed rule (CMS-9123-P), further specify FHIR adoption for payer-to-payer exchange.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] The CMS rules and Office of the National Coordinator for Health IT (ONC) Cures Act Final rule (HHS-ONC-0955-AA01) work in concert to drive FHIR adoption within their respective regulatory authorities.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] Further, other agencies are using existing rule-making authority, not derived from the Cures Act, to harmonize the regulatory landscape and ease FHIR adoption.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) Office of Civil Rights (OCR) has proposed to update the HIPAA privacy rule (HHS–OCR–0945–AA00) with an expanded right of access for personal health apps and disclosures between providers for care coordination.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] Unlike the CMS and ONC final rules, the OCR HIPAA privacy proposed rule is not specific to FHIR; however, OCR's emphasize on standards-based APIs clearly benefits FHIR adoption.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] In 2020, Brazil's Ministry of Health, by the IT Department of the SUS, started one of the world's largest platforms for national health interoperability, called the National Health Data Network, which uses HL7 FHIR r4 as a standard in all its information exchanges.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] In 2020, Israel's Ministry of Health began working towards the goal of promoting accessibility of information to patients and caregivers through the adoption of the FHIR standard in health organizations in Israel.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] Its first act was to create the IL-CORE work team to adapt the necessary components for localization and regulation in the health system in Israel.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] The ministry, in cooperation with the Nonprofit Organization 8400, created the FHIR IL community, whose purpose is to encourage the adoption of the standard in the Israeli healthcare system while cooperating with healthcare organizations and the industry.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] As part of a joint activity of the Ministry and 8400, a number of projects were launched for the implementation of FHIR in health management organizations (HMO) and hospitals, alongside other projects that are being independently promoted by healthcare organizations.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] In addition, the Ministry of Health allocated budgets to the HMOs and other organizations for the purpose of establishing organizational FHIR infrastructure.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] In the 2020 Eli Hurvitz Conference on Economy and Society, run by the Israel Democracy Institute it was estimated that the cost of implementing central FHIR modules of in the Israeli healthcare system is estimated at about 400 million NIS over 5 years.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] In 2023, the Israeli government began a legislative process to promote the sharing of information between organizations in the Israeli health ecosystem for the benefit of the patient, with an emphasis on patient empowerment and reduced information blocking.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] The proposed legislation also refers to the need to standardize the data by adopting the FHIR standard and utilizing standard terminologies, such as SNOMED-CT, both in source systems and in the data exchange process.
[src:fhir-health/fast-healthcare-interoperability-resources] The sharing of information will be with the patient's consent, and this consent will be given according to data buckets.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] The health domain provides an extremely wide variety of problems that can be tackled using computational techniques.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Health informatics is a multidisciplinary field that includes the study of the design, development, and application of computational innovations to improve health care.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] In academic institutions, health informatics includes research focuses on applications of artificial intelligence in healthcare and designing medical devices based on embedded systems.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] In some countries the term informatics is also used in the context of applying library science to data management in hospitals where it aims to develop methods and technologies for the acquisition, processing, and study of patient data, An umbrella term of biomedical informatics has been proposed.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Dutch former professor of medical informatics Jan van Bemmel has described medical informatics as the theoretical and practical aspects of information processing and communication based on knowledge and experience derived from processes in medicine and health care.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Clinicians collaborate with other health care and information technology professionals to develop health informatics tools which promote patient care that is safe, efficient, effective, timely, patient-centered, and equitable.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Many clinical informaticists are also computer scientists.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Telehealth is the distribution of health-related services and information via electronic information and telecommunication technologies.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] It allows long-distance patient and clinician contact, care, advice, reminders, education, intervention, monitoring, and remote admissions.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Telemedicine is sometimes used as a synonym, or is used in a more limited sense to describe remote clinical services, such as diagnosis and monitoring.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Remote monitoring, also known as self-monitoring or testing, enables medical professionals to monitor a patient remotely using various technological devices.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] This method is primarily used for managing chronic diseases or specific conditions, such as heart disease, diabetes mellitus, or asthma.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] These services can provide comparable health outcomes to traditional in-person patient encounters, supply greater satisfaction to patients, and may be cost-effective.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Telerehabilitation (or e-rehabilitation[40][41]) is the delivery of rehabilitation services over telecommunications networks and the Internet.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Most types of services fall into two categories: clinical assessment (the patient's functional abilities in his or her environment), and clinical therapy.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Some fields of rehabilitation practice that have explored telerehabilitation are: neuropsychology, speech-language pathology, audiology, occupational therapy, and physical therapy.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Telerehabilitation can deliver therapy to people who cannot travel to a clinic because the patient has a disability or because of travel time.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Telerehabilitation also allows experts in rehabilitation to engage in a clinical consultation at a distance.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] A pioneer in the use of artificial intelligence in healthcare was American biomedical informatician Edward H.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] This field deals with utilization of machine-learning algorithms and artificial intelligence, to emulate human cognition in the analysis, interpretation, and comprehension of complicated medical and healthcare data.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Specifically, AI is the ability of computer algorithms to approximate conclusions based solely on input data.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] AI programs are applied to practices such as diagnosis processes, treatment protocol development, drug development, personalized medicine, and patient monitoring and care.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] A large part of industry focus of implementation of AI in the healthcare sector is in the clinical decision support systems.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] As more data is collected, machine learning algorithms adapt and allow for more robust responses and solutions.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Numerous companies are exploring the possibilities of the incorporation of big data in the healthcare industry.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Many companies investigate the market opportunities through the realms of "data assessment, storage, management, and analysis technologies" which are all crucial parts of the healthcare industry.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Digital consultant apps like Babylon Health's GP at Hand, Ada Health, Alibaba Health Doctor You, KareXpert and Your.MD use AI to give medical consultation based on personal medical history and common medical knowledge.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Users report their symptoms into the app, which uses speech recognition to compare against a database of illnesses.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Babylon then offers a recommended action, taking into account the user's medical history.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Entrepreneurs in healthcare have been effectively using seven business model archetypes to take AI solution[buzzword] to the marketplace.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] These archetypes depend on the value generated for the target user (e.g. patient focus vs. healthcare provider and payer focus) and value capturing mechanisms (e.g. providing information or connecting stakeholders).
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] IFlytek launched a service robot "Xiao Man", which integrated artificial intelligence technology to identify the registered customer and provide personalized recommendations in medical areas.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] It also works in the field of medical imaging.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Similar robots are also being made by companies such as UBTECH ("Cruzr") and Softbank Robotics ("Pepper").
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] The Indian startup Haptik recently developed a WhatsApp chatbot which answers questions associated with the deadly coronavirus in India.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] With the market for AI expanding constantly, large tech companies such as Apple, Google, Amazon, and Baidu all have their own AI research divisions, as well as millions of dollars allocated for acquisition of smaller AI based companies.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Many automobile manufacturers are beginning to use machine learning healthcare in their cars as well.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Companies such as BMW, GE, Tesla, Toyota, and Volvo all have new research campaigns to find ways of learning a driver's vital statistics to ensure they are awake, paying attention to the road, and not under the influence of substances or in emotional distress.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Examples of projects in computational health informatics include the COACH project.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Computational health informatics aids in identifying population inequities.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Clinical research informatics (CRI) is a sub-field of health informatics that tries to improve the efficiency of clinical research by using informatics methods.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] CRI is a fairly new branch of informatics and has met growing pains as any up and coming field does.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Some issue CRI faces is the ability for the statisticians and the computer system architects to work with the clinical research staff in designing a system and lack of funding to support the development of a new system.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Researchers and the informatics team have a difficult time coordinating plans and ideas in order to design a system that is easy to use for the research team yet fits in the system requirements of the computer team.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] The lack of funding can be a hindrance to the development of the CRI.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Many organizations who are performing research are struggling to get financial support to conduct the research, much less invest that money in an informatics system that will not provide them any more income or improve the outcome of the research (Embi, 2009).
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Ability to integrate data from multiple clinical trials is an important part of clinical research informatics.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Initiatives, such as PhenX and Patient-Reported Outcomes Measurement Information System triggered a general effort to improve secondary use of data collected in past human clinical trials.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] CDE initiatives, for example, try to allow clinical trial designers to adopt standardized research instruments (electronic case report forms).
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] A parallel effort to standardizing how data is collected are initiatives that offer de-identified patient level clinical study data to be downloaded by researchers who wish to re-use this data.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Examples of such platforms are Project Data Sphere, dbGaP, ImmPort or Clinical Study Data Request.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Informatics issues in data formats for sharing results (plain CSV files, FDA endorsed formats, such as CDISC Study Data Tabulation Model) are important challenges within the field of clinical research informatics.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] One of the fundamental elements of biomedical and translation research is the use of integrated data repositories.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] A survey conducted in 2010 defined "integrated data repository" (IDR) as a data warehouse incorporating various sources of clinical data to support queries for a range of research-like functions.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Integrated data repositories are complex systems developed to solve a variety of problems ranging from identity management, protection of confidentiality, semantic and syntactic comparability of data from different sources, and most importantly convenient and flexible query.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Development of the field of clinical informatics led to the creation of large data sets with electronic health record data integrated with other data (such as genomic data).
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Types of data repositories include operational data stores (ODSs), clinical data warehouses (CDWs), clinical data marts, and clinical registries.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Operational data stores established for extracting, transferring and loading before creating warehouse or data marts.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Clinical registries repositories have long been in existence, but their contents are disease specific and sometimes considered archaic.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Clinical data stores and clinical data warehouses are considered fast and reliable.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Though these large integrated repositories have impacted clinical research significantly, it still faces challenges and barriers.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] One big problem is the requirement for ethical approval by the institutional review board (IRB) for each research analysis meant for publication.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Some research resources do not require IRB approval.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] For example, CDWs with data of deceased patients have been de-identified and IRB approval is not required for their usage.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Methods that adjust for bias (such as using propensity score matching methods) assume that a complete health record is captured.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Tools that examine data quality (e.g., point to missing data) help in discovering data quality problems.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Translational Bioinformatics (TBI) is a relatively new field that surfaced in the year of 2000 when human genome sequence was released.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] The commonly used definition of TBI is lengthy and could be found on the AMIA website.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] In simpler terms, TBI could be defined as a collection of colossal amounts of health related data (biomedical and genomic) and translation of the data into individually tailored clinical entities.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] When introduced in partnership with pharmaceuticals, bioinformatics comprised a base of knowledge of computational chemistry and molecular biology.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] These associations broadened the aspects of bioinformatics with pharmaceutical production.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Such processed translational computations decently enough to produce effective medicinal product.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Bioinformatics is attributed with that strict collaborative understanding today, where such pharmaceuticals work at reversing mutated molecular human DNA (Behl et al., 2021).
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] An important application of information engineering in medicine is medical signal processing.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] It refers to the generation, analysis, and use of signals, which could take many forms such as image, sound, electrical, or biological.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Imaging informatics and medical image computing develops computational and mathematical methods for solving problems pertaining to medical images and their use for biomedical research and clinical care.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Those fields aims to extract clinically relevant information or knowledge from medical images and computational analysis of the images.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] The methods can be grouped into several broad categories: image segmentation, image registration, image-based physiological modeling, and others.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] A medical robot is a robot used in the medical sciences.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] These are in most telemanipulators, which use the surgeon's activators on one side to control the "effector" on the other side.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Pathology informatics is a field that involves the use of information technology, computer systems, and data management to support and enhance the practice of pathology.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] It encompasses pathology laboratory operations, data analysis, and the interpretation of pathology-related information.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Worldwide use of computer technology in medicine began in the early 1950s with the rise of the computers.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] In 1949, Gustav Wagner established the first professional organization for informatics in Germany.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Specialized university departments and Informatics training programs began during the 1960s in France, Germany, Belgium and The Netherlands.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Medical informatics research units began to appear during the 1970s in Poland and in the U.S.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Since then the development of high-quality health informatics research, education and infrastructure has been a goal of the U.S. and the European Union.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] These constituencies accommodate professionals in and for the NHS, in academia and commercial service and solution providers.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p01] Since the 1970s the most prominent international coordinating body has been the International Medical Informatics Association (IMIA).
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The Argentinian health system is heterogeneous in its function, and because of that, the informatics developments show a heterogeneous stage.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Many private health care centers have developed systems, such as the Hospital Aleman of Buenos Aires, or the Hospital Italiano de Buenos Aires that also has a residence program for health informatics.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The first applications of computers to medicine and health care in Brazil started around 1968, with the installation of the first mainframes in public university hospitals, and the use of programmable calculators in scientific research applications.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In the 1970s, several Digital Corporation and Hewlett-Packard minicomputers were acquired for public and Armed Forces hospitals, and more intensively used for intensive-care unit, cardiology diagnostics, patient monitoring and other applications.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In Brazil, two universities are pioneers in teaching and research in medical informatics, both the University of São Paulo and the Federal University of São Paulo offer undergraduate programs highly qualified in the area as well as extensive graduate programs (MSc and PhD).
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In 2015 the Universidade Federal de Ciências da Saúde de Porto Alegre, Rio Grande do Sul, also started to offer undergraduate program.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Health Informatics projects in Canada are implemented provincially, with different provinces creating different systems.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] A national, federally funded, not-for-profit organisation called Canada Health Infoway was created in 2001 to foster the development and adoption of electronic health records across Canada.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] As of December 31, 2008, there were 276 EHR projects under way in Canadian hospitals, other health-care facilities, pharmacies and laboratories, with an investment value of $1.5-billion from Canada Health Infoway.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Even though the idea of using computers in medicine emerged as technology advanced in the early 20th century, it was not until the 1950s that informatics began to have an effect in the United States.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The earliest use of electronic digital computers for medicine was for dental projects in the 1950s at the United States National Bureau of Standards by Robert Ledley.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] During the mid-1950s, the United States Air Force (USAF) carried out several medical projects on its computers while also encouraging civilian agencies such as the National Academy of Sciences – National Research Council (NAS-NRC) and the National Institutes of Health (NIH) to sponsor such work.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Lusted published "Reasoning Foundations of Medical Diagnosis," a widely read article in *Science*, which introduced computing (especially operations research) techniques to medical workers.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Ledley and Lusted's article has remained influential for decades, especially within the field of medical decision making.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Guided by Ledley's late 1950s survey of computer use in biology and medicine (carried out for the NAS-NRC), and by his and Lusted's articles, the NIH undertook the first major effort to introduce computers to biology and medicine.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] This effort, carried out initially by the NIH's Advisory Committee on Computers in Research (ACCR), chaired by Lusted, spent over $40 million between 1960 and 1964 in order to establish dozens of large and small biomedical research centers in the US.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] One early (1960, non-ACCR) use of computers was to help quantify normal human movement, as a precursor to scientifically measuring deviations from normal, and design of prostheses.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The use of computers (IBM 650, 1620, and 7040) allowed analysis of a large sample size, and of more measurements and subgroups than had been previously practical with mechanical calculators, thus allowing an objective understanding of how human locomotion varies by age and body characteristics.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] A study co-author was Dean of the Marquette University College of Engineering; this work led to discrete Biomedical Engineering departments there and elsewhere.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The next steps, in the mid-1960s, were the development (sponsored largely by the NIH) of expert systems such as MYCIN and Internist-I.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In 1965, the National Library of Medicine started to use MEDLINE and MEDLARS.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In the 1970s and 1980s it was the most commonly used programming language for clinical applications.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The MUMPS operating system was used to support MUMPS language specifications.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] As of 2004, a descendant of this system is being used in the United States Veterans Affairs hospital system.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The VA has the largest enterprise-wide health information system that includes an electronic medical record, known as the Veterans Health Information Systems and Technology Architecture (VistA).
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] A graphical user interface known as the Computerized Patient Record System (CPRS) allows health care providers to review and update a patient's electronic medical record at any of the VA's over 1,000 health care facilities.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Collen, a physician working for Kaiser Permanente's Division of Research, developed computerized systems to automate many aspects of multi-phased health checkups.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] These systems became the basis the larger medical databases Kaiser Permanente developed during the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The American Medical Informatics Association presents the Morris F.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Collen Award of Excellence for an individual's lifetime achievement in biomedical informatics.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In the 1970s a growing number of commercial vendors began to market practice management and electronic medical records systems.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Although many products exist, only a small number of health practitioners use fully featured electronic health care records systems.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Slack, MD, and Howard Bleich, MD, co-founded the academic division of clinical informatics (DCI) at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center and Harvard Medical School.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Warner Slack is a pioneer of the development of the electronic patient medical history, and in 1977 Dr.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Bleich created the first user-friendly search engine for the worlds biomedical literature.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Computerised systems involved in patient care have led to a number of changes.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Such changes have led to improvements in electronic health records which are now capable of sharing medical information among multiple health care stakeholders (Zahabi, Kaber, & Swangnetr, 2015); thereby, supporting the flow of patient information through various modalities of care.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] One opportunity for electronic health records (EHR) to be even more effectively used is to utilize natural language processing for searching and analyzing notes and text that would otherwise be inaccessible for review.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] These can be further developed through ongoing collaboration between software developers and end-users of natural language processing tools within the electronic health EHRs.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Computer use today involves a broad ability which includes but is not limited to physician diagnosis and documentation, patient appointment scheduling, and billing.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Many researchers in the field have identified an increase in the quality of health care systems, decreased errors by health care workers, and lastly savings in time and money (Zahabi, Kaber, & Swangnetr, 2015).
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The system, however, is not perfect and will continue to require improvement.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Frequently cited factors of concern involve usability, safety, accessibility, and user-friendliness (Zahabi, Kaber, & Swangnetr, 2015).
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Warner, one of the fathers of medical informatics, founded the Department of Medical Informatics at the University of Utah in 1968.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The American Medical Informatics Association (AMIA) has an award named after him on application of informatics to medicine.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The American Medical Informatics Association created a, board certification for medical informatics from the American Board of Preventive Medicine.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The American Nurses Credentialing Center offers a board certification in Nursing Informatics.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The CIIP certification requires documented experience working in Imaging Informatics, formal testing and is a limited time credential requiring renewal every five years.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The exam tests for a combination of IT technical knowledge, clinical understanding, and project management experience thought to represent the typical workload of a PACS administrator or other radiology IT clinical support role.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Certifications from PARCA (PACS Administrators Registry and Certifications Association) are also recognized.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The five PARCA certifications are tiered from entry-level to architect level.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The American Health Information Management Association offers credentials in medical coding, analytics, and data administration, such as Registered Health Information Administrator and Certified Coding Associate.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Certifications are widely requested by employers in health informatics, and overall the demand for certified informatics workers in the United States is outstripping supply.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The American Health Information Management Association reports that only 68% of applicants pass certification exams on the first try.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Bush signed Executive Order 13335, creating the Office of the National Coordinator for Health Information Technology (ONCHIT) as a division of the U.S.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Department of Health and Human Services (HHS).
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The mission of this office is widespread adoption of interoperable electronic health records (EHRs) in the US within 10 years.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] See quality improvement organizations for more information on federal initiatives in this area.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In 2014 the Department of Education approved an advanced Health Informatics Undergraduate program that was submitted by the University of South Alabama.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The program is designed to provide specific Health Informatics education, and is the only program in the country with a Health Informatics Lab.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The program is housed in the School of Computing in Shelby Hall, a recently completed $50 million state of the art teaching facility.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The University of South Alabama awarded David L.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Loeser on May 10, 2014, with the first Health Informatics degree.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The program currently is scheduled to have 100+ students awarded by 2016.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The Certification Commission for Healthcare Information Technology (CCHIT), a private nonprofit group, was funded in 2005 by the U.S.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Department of Health and Human Services to develop a set of standards for electronic health records (EHR) and supporting networks, and certify vendors who meet them.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In July 2006, CCHIT released its first list of 22 certified ambulatory EHR products, in two different announcements.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Harvard Medical School added a department of biomedical informatics in 2015.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The University of Cincinnati in partnership with Cincinnati Children's Hospital Medical Center created a biomedical informatics (BMI) Graduate certificate program and in 2015 began a BMI PhD program.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The joint program allows for researchers and students to observe the impact their work has on patient care directly as discoveries are translated from bench to bedside.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The European Commission's preference, as exemplified in the 5th Framework as well as currently pursued pilot projects, is for Free/Libre and Open Source Software (FLOSS) for health care.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The European Union's Member States are committed to sharing their best practices and experiences to create a European eHealth Area, thereby improving access to and quality health care at the same time as stimulating growth in a promising new industrial sector.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The European eHealth Action Plan plays a fundamental role in the European Union's strategy.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Work on this initiative involves a collaborative approach among several parts of the Commission services.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The European Institute for Health Records is involved in the promotion of high quality electronic health record systems in the European Union.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The broad history of health informatics has been captured in the book *UK Health Computing: Recollections and reflections*, Hayes G, Barnett D (Eds.), BCS (May 2008) by those active in the field, predominantly members of BCS Health and its constituent groups.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The book describes the path taken as "early development of health informatics was unorganized and idiosyncratic".
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In the early 1950s, it was prompted by those involved in NHS finance and only in the early 1960s did solutions including those in pathology (1960), radiotherapy (1962), immunization (1963), and primary care (1968) emerge.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Many of these solutions, even in the early 1970s were developed in-house by pioneers in the field to meet their own requirements.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In part, this was due to some areas of health services (for example the immunization and vaccination of children) still being provided by Local Authorities.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] There are different models of health informatics delivery in each of the home countries (England, Scotland, Northern Ireland and Wales) but some bodies like UKCHIP (see below) operate for those 'in and for' all the home countries and beyond.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] NPfIT originally divided the country into five regions, with strategic 'systems integration' contracts awarded to one of several Local Service Providers (LSP).
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The various specific technical solutions were required to connect securely with the NHS 'Spine', a system designed to broker data between different systems and care settings.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] NPfIT fell significantly behind schedule and its scope and design were being revised in real time, exacerbated by media and political lambasting of the Programme's spend (past and projected) against the proposed budget.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In 2010 a consultation was launched as part of the new Conservative/Liberal Democrat Coalition Government's White Paper "Liberating the NHS".
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] This initiative provided little in the way of innovative thinking, primarily re-stating existing strategies within the proposed new context of the Coalition's vision for the NHS.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Almost all general practices in England and Wales are computerized under the GP Systems of Choice programme, and patients have relatively extensive computerized primary care clinical records.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] System choice is the responsibility of individual general practices and while there is no single, standardized GP system, it sets relatively rigid minimum standards of performance and functionality for vendors to adhere to.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Interoperation between primary and secondary care systems is rather primitive.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] It is hoped that a focus on interworking (for interfacing and integration) standards will stimulate synergy between primary and secondary care in sharing necessary information to support the care of individuals.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Notable successes to date are in the electronic requesting and viewing of test results, and in some areas, GPs have access to digital x-ray images from secondary care systems.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In 2019 the GP Systems of Choice framework was replaced by the GP IT Futures framework, which is to be the main vehicle used by clinical commissioning groups to buy services for GPs.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] This is intended to increase competition in an area that is dominated by EMIS and TPP.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] 69 technology companies offering more than 300 solutions have been accepted on to the new framework.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Wales has a dedicated Health Informatics function that supports NHS Wales in leading on the new integrated digital information services and promoting Health Informatics as a career.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The British Computer Society (BCS) provides 4 different professional registration levels for Health and Care Informatics Professionals: Practitioner, Senior Practitioner, Advanced Practitioner, and Leading Practitioner.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The Faculty of Clinical Informatics (FCI) is the professional membership society for health and social care professionals in clinical informatics offering Fellowship, Membership and Associateship.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] BCS and FCI are member organizations of the Federation for Informatics Professionals in Health and Social Care (FedIP), a collaboration between the leading professional bodies in health and care informatics supporting the development of the informatics professions.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The Faculty of Clinical Informatics has produced a Core Competency Framework that describes the wide range of skills needed by practitioners.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In the Netherlands, health informatics is currently a priority for research and implementation.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The Netherlands Federation of University medical centers (NFU) has created the *Citrienfonds*, which includes the programs eHealth and Registration at the Source.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The Netherlands also has the national organizations Society for Healthcare Informatics (VMBI) and Nictiz, the national center for standardization and eHealth.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In Asia and Australia-New Zealand, the regional group called the Asia Pacific Association for Medical Informatics (APAMI) was established in 1994 and now consists of more than 15 member regions in the Asia Pacific Region.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The Australasian College of Health Informatics (ACHI) is the professional association for health informatics in the Asia-Pacific region.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] It represents the interests of a broad range of clinical and non-clinical professionals working within the health informatics sphere through a commitment to quality, standards and ethical practice.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] ACHI is an academic institutional member of the International Medical Informatics Association (IMIA) and a full member of the Australian Council of Professions.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] ACHI is a sponsor of the "e-Journal for Health Informatics", an indexed and peer-reviewed professional journal.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] ACHI has also supported the "Australian Health Informatics Education Council" (AHIEC) since its founding in 2009.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Although there are a number of health informatics organizations in Australia, the Health Informatics Society of Australia (HISA) is regarded as the major umbrella group and is a member of the International Medical Informatics Association (IMIA).
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Nursing informaticians were the driving force behind the formation of HISA, which is now a company limited by guarantee of the members.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The membership comes from across the informatics spectrum that is from students to corporate affiliates.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] HISA has a number of branches (Queensland, New South Wales, Victoria and Western Australia) as well as special interest groups such as nursing (NIA), pathology, aged and community care, industry and medical imaging (Conrick, 2006).
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] After 20 years, China performed a successful transition from its planned economy to a socialist market economy.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Along this change, China's health care system also experienced a significant reform to follow and adapt to this historical revolution.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In 2003, the data (released from Ministry of Health of the People's Republic of China (MoH)), indicated that the national health care-involved expenditure was up to RMB 662.33 billion totally, which accounted for about 5.56% of nationwide gross domestic products.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Before the 1980s, the entire health care costs were covered in central government annual budget.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Since that, the construct of health care-expended supporters started to change gradually.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Most of the expenditure was contributed by health insurance schemes and private spending, which corresponded to 40% and 45% of total expenditure, respectively.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Meanwhile, the financially governmental contribution was decreased to 10% only.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] On the other hand, by 2004, up to 296,492 health care facilities were recorded in statistic summary of MoH, and an average of 2.4 clinical beds per 1000 people were mentioned as well.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Therefore, substantial resources were collected to build China's own health informatics system.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Most of these resources were arranged to construct hospital information system (HIS), which was aimed to minimize unnecessary waste and repetition, subsequently to promote the efficiency and quality-control of health care.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] By 2004, China had successfully spread HIS through approximately 35–40% of nationwide hospitals.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] However, the dispersion of hospital-owned HIS varies critically.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In the east part of China, over 80% of hospitals constructed HIS, in northwest of China the equivalent was no more than 20%.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] China has four tiers in its health care system.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The first tier is street health and workplace clinics and these are cheaper than hospitals in terms of medical billing and act as prevention centers.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The second tier is district and enterprise hospitals along with specialist clinics and these provide the second level of care.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The third tier is provisional and municipal general hospitals and teaching hospitals which provided the third level of care.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In a tier of its own is the national hospitals which are governed by the Ministry of Health.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] China has been greatly improving its health informatics since it finally opened its doors to the outside world and joined the World Trade Organization (WTO).
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In 2001, it was reported that China had 324,380 medical institutions and the majority of those were clinics.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The reason for that is that clinics are prevention centers and Chinese people like using traditional Chinese medicine as opposed to Western medicine and it usually works for the minor cases.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] China has also been improving its higher education in regards to health informatics.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] At the end of 2002, there were 77 medical universities and medical colleges.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] There were 48 university medical colleges which offered bachelor, master, and doctorate degrees in medicine.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] There were 21 higher medical specialty institutions that offered diploma degrees so in total, there were 147 higher medical and educational institutions.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Since joining the WTO, China has been working hard to improve its education system and bring it up to international standards.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] SARS played a large role in China quickly improving its health care system.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Back in 2003, there was an outbreak of SARS and that made China hurry to spread HIS or Hospital Information System and more than 80% of hospitals had HIS.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] China had been comparing itself to Korea's health care system and figuring out how it can better its own system.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] There was a study done that surveyed six hospitals in China that had HIS.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The results were that doctors did not use computers as much so it was concluded that it was not used as much for clinical practice than it was for administrative purposes.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The survey asked if the hospitals created any websites and it was concluded that only four of them had created websites and that three had a third-party company create it for them and one was created by the hospital staff.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In conclusion, all of them agreed or strongly agreed that providing health information on the Internet should be utilized.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Collected information at different times, by different participants or systems could frequently lead to issues of misunderstanding, dis-comparing or dis-exchanging.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] To design an issues-minor system, health care providers realized that certain standards were the basis for sharing information and interoperability, however a system lacking standards would be a large impediment to interfere the improvement of corresponding information systems.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Given that the standardization for health informatics depends on the authorities, standardization events must be involved with government and the subsequently relevant funding and supports were critical.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In 2003, the Ministry of Health released the Development Lay-out of National Health Informatics (2003–2010) indicating the identification of standardization for health informatics which is 'combining adoption of international standards and development of national standards'.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In China, the establishment of standardization was initially facilitated with the development of vocabulary, classification and coding, which is conducive to reserve and transmit information for premium management at national level.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] By 2006, 55 international/ domestic standards of vocabulary, classification and coding have served in hospital information system.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In 2003, the 10th revision of the International Statistical Classification of Diseases and Related Health Problems (ICD-10) and the ICD-10 Clinical Modification (ICD-10-CM) were adopted as standards for diagnostic classification and acute care procedure classification.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Simultaneously, the International Classification of Primary Care (ICPC) were translated and tested in China 's local applied environment.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Another coding standard, named Logical Observation Identifiers Names and Codes (LOINC), was applied to serve as general identifiers for clinical observation in hospitals.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Personal identifier codes were widely employed in different information systems, involving name, sex, nationality, family relationship, educational level and job occupation.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] However, these codes within different systems are inconsistent, when sharing between different regions.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Considering this large quantity of vocabulary, classification and coding standards between different jurisdictions, the health care provider realized that using multiple systems could generate issues of resource wasting and a non-conflicting national level standard was beneficial and necessary.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Identify the classes, relationships and attributes of national health information framework.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The deficiencies that were found are listed in the following.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The shortage of supporting on different types of data and reference.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Considering only ICD-9 is referenced as China's external international coding systems, other similar systems, such as SNOMED CT in clinical terminology presentation, cannot be considered as familiar for Chinese specialists, which could lead to internationally information-sharing deficiency.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The lack of more generic and extensible lower level data structures.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] China's large and complex EHR Standard was constructed for all medical domains.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] However, the specific and time-frequent attributes of clinical data elements, value sets and templates identified that this once-for-all purpose cannot lead to practical consequence.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In Hong Kong, a computerized patient record system called the Clinical Management System (CMS) has been developed by the Hospital Authority since 1994.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] This system has been deployed at all the sites of the authority (40 hospitals and 120 clinics).
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] It is used for up to 2 million transactions daily by 30,000 clinical staff.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The comprehensive records of 7 million patients are available on-line in the electronic patient record (ePR), with data integrated from all sites.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Since 2004 radiology image viewing has been added to the ePR, with radiography images from any HA site being available as part of the ePR.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The Hong Kong Hospital Authority placed particular attention to the governance of clinical systems development, with input from hundreds of clinicians being incorporated through a structured process.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The health informatics section in the Hospital Authority has a close relationship with the information technology department and clinicians to develop health care systems for the organization to support the service to all public hospitals and clinics in the region.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The Hong Kong Society of Medical Informatics (HKSMI) was established in 1987 to promote the use of information technology in health care.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The eHealth Consortium has been formed to bring together clinicians from both the private and public sectors, medical informatics professionals and the IT industry to further promote IT in health care in Hong Kong.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Since 2010, the Ministry of Health (MoH) has been working on the Malaysian Health Data Warehouse (MyHDW) project.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] MyHDW aims to meet the diverse needs of timely health information provision and management, and acts as a platform for the standardization and integration of health data from a variety of sources (Health Informatics Centre, 2013).
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The Ministry of Health has embarked on introducing the electronic Hospital Information Systems (HIS) in several public hospitals including Putrajaya Hospital, Serdang Hospital and Selayang Hospital.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Similarly, under Ministry of Higher Education, hospitals such as University of Malaya Medical Centre (UMMC) and University Kebangsaan Malaysia Medical Centre (UKMMC) are also using HIS for healthcare delivery.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] A hospital information system (HIS) is a comprehensive, integrated information system designed to manage the administrative, financial and clinical aspects of a hospital.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] As an area of medical informatics, the aim of hospital information system is to achieve the best possible support of patient care and administration by electronic data processing.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] HIS plays a vital role in planning, initiating, organizing and controlling the operations of the subsystems of the hospital and thus provides a synergistic organization in the process.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Health informatics is taught at five New Zealand universities.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The most mature and established programme has been offered for over a decade at Otago.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Health Informatics New Zealand (HINZ), is the national organization that advocates for health informatics.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] HINZ organizes a conference every year and also publishes a journal, *Healthcare Informatics Review Online*.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The Saudi Association for Health Information (SAHI) was established in 2006 to work under direct supervision of King Saud bin Abdulaziz University for Health Sciences to practice public activities, develop theoretical and applicable knowledge, and provide scientific and applicable studies.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The Russian health care system is based on the principles of the Soviet health care system, which was oriented on mass prophylaxis, prevention of infection and epidemic diseases, vaccination and immunization of the population on a socially protected basis.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] One of the main issues of the post-Soviet medical health care system was the absence of the united system providing optimization of work for medical institutes with one, single database and structured appointment schedule and hence hours-long lines.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Efficiency of medical workers might have been also doubtful because of the paperwork administrating or lost book records.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Along with the development of the information systems IT and health care departments in Moscow agreed on design of a system that would improve public services of health care institutes.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Tackling the issues appearing in the existing system, the Moscow Government ordered that the design of a system would provide simplified electronic booking to public clinics and automate the work of medical workers on the first level.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Besides that, the system contains information about availability of the medical institutions and various doctors.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The implementation of the system started in 2013 with the organization of one computerized database for all patients in the city, including a front-end for the users.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] EMIAS was implemented in Moscow and the region and it is planned that the project should extend to most parts of the country.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] As many health care systems are making an effort to have patient records more readily available to them via the internet, it is important that providers implement security standards in order to ensure that the patients' information is safe.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] They have to be able to assure confidentiality, integrity, and security of the people, process, and technology.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Since there is also the possibility of payments being made through this system, it is vital that this aspect of their private information will also be protected through cryptography.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The use of technology in health care settings has become popular and this trend is expected to continue.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Various health care facilities had instigated different kinds of health information technology systems in the provision of patient care, such as electronic health records (EHRs), computerized charting, etc.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The growing popularity of health information technology systems and the escalation in the amount of health information that can be exchanged and transferred electronically increased the risk of potential infringement in patients' privacy and confidentiality.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] This concern triggered the establishment of strict measures by both policymakers and individual facility to ensure patient privacy and confidentiality.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] One of the federal laws enacted to safeguard patient's health information (medical record, billing information, treatment plan, etc.) and to guarantee patient's privacy is the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act of 1996 or HIPAA.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] HIPAA gives patients the autonomy and control over their own health records.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] As of September 7, 2016, there are roughly 235 informatics journals listed in the National Library of Medicine (NLM) catalog of journals.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The *Journal Citation Reports* for 2018 gives the top three journals in medical informatics as the *Journal of Medical Internet Research* (impact factor of 4.945), *JMIR mHealth and uHealth* (4.301) and the *Journal of the American Medical Informatics Association* (4.292).
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In the United States, *clinical informatics* is a subspecialty within several medical specialties.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] For example, in pathology, the American Board of Pathology offers clinical informatics certification for pathologists who have completed 24 months of related training, and the American Board of Preventive Medicine offers clinical informatics certification within preventive medicine.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In October 2011 American Board of Medical Specialties (ABMS), the organization overseeing the certification of specialist MDs in the United States, announced the creation of MD-only physician certification in clinical informatics.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The first examination for board certification in the subspecialty of clinical informatics was offered in October 2013 by American Board of Preventive Medicine (ABPM) with 432 passing to become the 2014 inaugural class of Diplomates in clinical informatics.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Fellowship programs exist for physicians who wish to become board-certified in clinical informatics.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] Physicians must have graduated from a medical school in the United States or Canada, or a school located elsewhere that is approved by the ABPM.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] In addition, they must complete a primary residency program such as Internal Medicine (or any of the 24 subspecialties recognized by the ABMS) and be eligible to become licensed to practice medicine in the state where their fellowship program is located.
[src:fhir-health/health-informatics-p02] The fellowship program is 24 months in length, with fellows dividing their time between Informatics rotations, didactic method, research, and clinical work in their primary specialty.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] Health organizations typically have many different computer systems used to process different patient administration or clinical tasks, such as billing, medication management, patient tracking, and documentation.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] All of these systems should communicate, or "interface", with each other when they receive new information or when they wish to retrieve information.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] HL7 International specifies a number of flexible standards, guidelines, and methodologies by which these healthcare systems can communicate with each other.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] The standards allow for easier 'interoperability' of healthcare data as it is shared and processed uniformly and consistently by the different systems.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] This allows clinical and non-clinical data to be shared more easily, theoretically improving patient care and health system performance.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] The HL7 version 2 standard (also known as Pipehat) supports the day-to-day workflow of a hospital: administrative tasks, billing, logistics, and clinical processes such as orders and results.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] It was first released in 1987 and has been revised regularly since, producing more than ten versions (2.1 through 2.9).
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] The v2.x versions are backward compatible with one another, so a message built to version 2.3 will still be understood by an application that supports version 2.6.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] Unlike newer HL7 standards, version 2.x messages are written as plain delimited text rather than XML.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] Two further characters round out the syntax: a tilde (`~`) marks repeated values within a field, and since HL7v2.7 a number sign (`#`) is the default truncation character.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] The example below is an admission message.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] `MSH` is the header; `PID` carries the patient's identity; `PV1` carries details of the visit.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] In the PID segment, the patient's name field contains three components separated by carets, family name (`KLEINSAMPLE`), given name (`BARRY`) and middle initial (`Q`), illustrating the field/component split described above.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] This flexibility has allowed HL7 v2.x to interconnect a wide range of hospital systems, from patient administration to electronic health records to specialised laboratory and radiology systems, and it remains supported by every major health informatics vendor in the United States.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] The HL7 version 3 standard has the aim to support all healthcare workflows.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] Development of version 3 started around 1995, resulting in an initial standard publication in 2005.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] The v3 standard, as opposed to version 2, is based on a formal methodology (the HDF) and object-oriented principles.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] The Reference Information Model (RIM) is the cornerstone of the HL7 Version 3 development process and an essential part of the HL7 V3 development methodology.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] RIM expresses the data content needed in a specific clinical or administrative context and provides an explicit representation of the semantic and lexical connections that exist between the information carried in the fields of HL7 messages.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] The HL7 Version 3 Development Framework (HDF) is a continuously evolving process that seeks to develop specifications that facilitate interoperability between healthcare systems.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] The HL7 RIM, vocabulary specifications, and model-driven process of analysis and design combine to make HL7 Version 3 one methodology for the development of consensus-based standards for healthcare information systems interoperability.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] The HDF is the most current edition of the HL7 V3 development methodology.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] The HDF not only documents messaging, but also the processes, tools, actors, rules, and artifacts relevant to the development of all HL7 standard specifications.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] Eventually, the HDF will encompass all of the HL7 standard specifications, including any new standards resulting from the analysis of electronic health record architectures and requirements.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] HL7 specifications draw upon codes and vocabularies from a variety of sources.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] The V3 vocabulary work ensures that the systems implementing HL7 specifications have an unambiguous understanding of the code sources and code value domains they are using.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] The HL7 version 3 messaging standard defines a series of Secure Text messages (called *interactions*) to support all healthcare workflows.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] The HL7 Clinical Document Architecture (CDA) is an XML-based markup standard intended to specify the encoding, structure and semantics of clinical documents for exchange.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] The standard was jointly published with ISO as ISO/HL7 27932.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] The Continuity of Care Document framework is a US-specific standard for the exchange of medical summaries, based on the Clinical Document Architecture standard.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] Structured Product Labeling describes the published information that accompanies a medicine, based on HL7 Version 3.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] CCOW, or "Clinical Context Object Workgroup," is a standard protocol designed to enable disparate applications to share user context and patient context in real-time, and at the user-interface level.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] CCOW implementations typically require a CCOW vault system to manage user security between applications.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] Fast Healthcare Interoperability Resources is a modern interoperability specification from HL7 International designed to be easier to implement, more open, and more extensible than HL7 versions 2.x or 3.x.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] It leverages a modern web-based suite of API technology, including a HTTP-based RESTful protocol, HTML and Cascading Style Sheets for user interface integration, a choice of JSON or XML for data representation, OAuth for authorization and Atom for query results.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] The main purpose of the FHIR standard is to ensure interoperability between different computer systems.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] It defines the data format and protocol for exchanging medical information, regardless of how it is stored in these systems.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] The HL7 Services-Aware Enterprise Architecture Framework (SAIF) provides consistency between all HL7 artifacts, and enables a standardized approach to Enterprise Architecture (EA) development and implementation, and a way to measure the consistency.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] SAIF is a way of thinking about producing specifications that explicitly describe the governance, conformance, compliance, and behavioral semantics that are needed to achieve computable semantic working interoperability.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] The intended information transmission technology might use a messaging, document exchange, or service approach.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] SAIF is the framework that is required to rationalize interoperability of other standards.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] SAIF is an architecture for achieving interoperability, but it is not a whole-solution design for enterprise architecture management.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] The Arden syntax is a language for encoding medical knowledge.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] HL7 International adopted and oversees the standard beginning with Arden syntax 2.0.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] These Medical Logic Modules (MLMs) are used in the clinical setting as they can contain sufficient knowledge to make single medical decisions.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] They can produce alerts, diagnoses, and interpretations along with quality assurance function and administrative support.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] An MLM must run on a computer that meets the minimum system requirements and has the correct program installed.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] Then, the MLM can give advice for when and where it is needed.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] Clinical quality language is being used for a variety of clinical applications including WHO SMART guidelines where it is used for encoding decision logic and performance indicators.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] The Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services adopted CQL for clinical quality measure specifications since 2019.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] CQL allows modular and flexible expression of logic and is both human-readable and machine processable.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] An implementation of CQL was open sourced and published by the National Committee for Quality Assurance in 2023 with the aim of encouraging adoption of the language.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] Functional specifications for an electronic health record.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] An OBR Segment carries information about an exam, diagnostic study/observation.
[src:fhir-health/health-level-7] It is a required segment in an ORM (order message) or an ORU (Observation Result) message.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Types of interoperability include **syntactic interoperability**, where two systems can communicate with each other, and cross-domain interoperability, where multiple organizations work together and exchange information.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] If two or more systems use common data formats and communication protocols, then they are capable of communicating with each other, and they exhibit *syntactic interoperability*.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] XML and SQL are examples of common data formats and protocols.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Low-level data formats also contribute to syntactic interoperability, ensuring that alphabetical characters are stored in the same ASCII or a Unicode format in all the communicating systems.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Beyond the ability of two or more computer systems to exchange information, semantic interoperability is the ability to automatically interpret the information exchanged meaningfully and accurately in order to produce useful results as defined by the end users of both systems.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] To achieve semantic interoperability, both sides must refer to a common information exchange reference model.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The content of the information exchange requests are unambiguously defined: what is sent is the same as what is understood.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Cross-domain interoperability involves multiple social, organizational, political, legal entities working together for a common interest or information exchange.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Interoperability implies exchanges between a range of products, or similar products from several different vendors, or even between past and future revisions of the same product.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Interoperability may be developed *post-facto*, as a special measure between two products, while excluding the rest, by using open standards.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] When a vendor is forced to adapt its system to a dominant system that is not based on open standards, it is compatibility, not interoperability.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Open standards rely on a broadly consultative and inclusive group, including representatives from vendors, academics and others holding a stake in the development that discusses and debates the technical and economic merits, demerits and feasibility of a proposed common protocol.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] After the doubts and reservations of all members are addressed, the resulting common document is endorsed as a *common standard*.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] This document may be subsequently released to the public, and henceforth becomes an *open standard*.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] It is usually published and is available freely or at a nominal cost to any and all comers, with *no further encumbrances*.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The vendors' products compete on the quality of their implementation, user interface, ease of use, performance, price, and a host of other factors, while keeping the customer's data intact and transferable even if they choose to switch to another competing product for business reasons.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] However, while "open" is a necessary condition for an interoperabilty standard, it is not a sufficient condition.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] For example, the standard-setting processes for the Fortran, C, and C++ languages are open, with a broadly-inclusive consultative group.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] But the resulting standards are not interoperability standards.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The data itself may be encumbered, e.g., by patents or pricing, leading to a dependence of all competing solutions on the original vendor, and possibly leading to a revenue stream from the competitors' customers back to the original vendor.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] This revenue stream is the result of the original product's market dominance and not a result of any innate superiority.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Alternatively, it can be argued that even open processes are subject to the weight of past implementations and imperfect past designs and that the power of the dominant vendor to unilaterally correct or improve the system and impose the changes to all users facilitates innovation.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Lack of an open standard can also become problematic for the customers, as in the case of the original vendor's inability to fix a certain problem that is an artifact of technical limitations in the original product.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Speaking from an e-government perspective, interoperability refers to the collaboration ability of cross-border services for citizens, businesses and public administrations.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Exchanging data can be a challenge due to language barriers, different specifications of formats, varieties of categorizations and other hindrances.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] If data is interpreted differently, collaboration is limited, takes longer and is inefficient.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] For instance, if a citizen of country A wants to purchase land in country B, the person will be asked to submit the proper address data.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Address data in both countries includes full name details, street name and number, as well as a postal code.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The order of the address details might vary.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] In the same language, it is not an obstacle to order the provided address data, but across language barriers, it becomes difficult.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] If the language uses a different writing system it is almost impossible if no translation tools are available.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Interoperability is used by researchers in the context of urban flood risk management.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Cities and urban areas worldwide are expanding, which creates complex spaces with many interactions between the environment, infrastructure and people.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] To address this complexity and manage water in urban areas appropriately, a system of systems approach to water and flood control is necessary.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] At the strategic level, interoperability is an enabler for coalition building.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] It facilitates meaningful contributions by coalition partners.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] At this level, interoperability issues center on harmonizing world views, strategies, doctrines, and force structures.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Interoperability is an element of coalition willingness to work together over the long term to achieve and maintain shared interests against common threats.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Interoperability at the operational and tactical levels is where strategic interoperability and technological interoperability come together to help allies shape the environment, manage crises, and win wars.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The benefits of interoperability at the operational and tactical levels generally derive from the interchangeability of force elements and units.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] *Technological interoperability* reflects the interfaces between organizations and systems.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] It focuses on communications and computers but also involves the technical capabilities of systems and the resulting mission compatibility between the systems and data of coalition partners.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] At the technological level, the benefits of interoperability come primarily from their impacts at the operational and tactical levels in terms of enhancing flexibility.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Because first responders need to be able to communicate during wide-scale emergencies, interoperability is an important issue for law enforcement, firefighting, emergency medical services, and other public health and safety departments.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] It has been a major area of investment and research over the last 12 years.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Widely disparate and incompatible hardware impedes the exchange of information between agencies.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Agencies' information systems, such as computer-aided dispatch systems and records management systems, functioned largely in isolation, in so-called *information islands*.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Agencies tried to bridge this isolation with inefficient, stopgap methods while large agencies began implementing limited interoperable systems.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] These approaches were inadequate and, in the US, the lack of interoperability in the public safety realm became evident during the 9/11 attacks on the Pentagon and World Trade Center structures.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Further evidence of a lack of interoperability surfaced when agencies tackled the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] In contrast to the overall national picture, some states, including Utah, have already made great strides forward.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The Utah Highway Patrol and other departments in Utah have created a statewide data sharing network.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The Commonwealth of Virginia is one of the leading states in the United States in improving interoperability.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The Interoperability Coordinator leverages a regional structure to better allocate grant funding around the Commonwealth so that all areas have an opportunity to improve communications interoperability.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The State of Washington seeks to enhance interoperability statewide.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Washington recognizes that collaborating on system design and development for wireless radio systems enables emergency responder agencies to efficiently provide additional services, increase interoperability, and reduce long-term costs.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] This work saves the lives of emergency personnel and the citizens they serve.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The U.S. government is making an effort to overcome the nation's lack of public safety interoperability.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The Department of Homeland Security's Office for Interoperability and Compatibility (OIC) is pursuing the SAFECOM and CADIP and Project 25 programs, which are designed to help agencies as they integrate their CAD and other IT systems.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] This project will partner the OIC with agencies in several locations, including Silicon Valley.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] This program will use case studies to identify the best practices and challenges associated with linking CAD systems across jurisdictional boundaries.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] These lessons will create the tools and resources public safety agencies can use to build interoperable CAD systems and communicate across local, state, and federal boundaries.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Governance entities can increase interoperability through their legislative and executive powers.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Conversely, government-mandated interoperability has been heavily criticized as leading to monopolies that become too big to fail.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] For example, the United States Securities and Exchange Commission's implementation of 1975 amendments to the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 that were intended to ensure interoperability was blamed for driving all regional clearinghouses and depositories out of business in the United States.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] As a result, the National Securities Clearing Corporation is the sole clearinghouse; the Depository Trust Company is the sole repository; and their parent, the Depository Trust & Clearing Corporation, has enormous market power over central counterparty clearing in the United States.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] In contrast, the federal government of the United States did not attempt to mandate or regulate credit card interoperability.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] This allowed credit card networks to naturally develop interoperability (in the sense that almost every payment terminal can automatically accept almost every credit card), so that Visa Inc. was not left as the last credit card network standing.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Desktop interoperability is a subset of software interoperability.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] In the early days, the focus of interoperability was to integrate web applications with other web applications.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Over time, open-system containers were developed to create a virtual desktop environment in which these applications could be registered and then communicate with each other using simple publish–subscribe patterns.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Rudimentary UI capabilities were also supported, allowing windows to be grouped with other windows.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Today, desktop interoperability has evolved into full-service platforms that include container support, basic exchange between web and web, but also native support for other application types and advanced window management.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The very latest interop platforms also include application services such as universal search, notifications, user permissions and preferences, 3rd party application connectors and language adapters for in-house applications.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Search interoperability refers to the ability of two or more information collections to be searched by a single query.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Specifically related to web-based search, the challenge of interoperability stems from the fact that designers of web resources typically have little or no need to concern themselves with exchanging information with other web resources.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Federated Search technology, which does not place format requirements on the data owner, has emerged as one solution to search interoperability challenges.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] In addition, standards, such as Open Archives Initiative Protocol for Metadata Harvesting, Resource Description Framework, and SPARQL, have emerged that also help address the issue of search interoperability related to web resources.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Such standards also address broader topics of interoperability, such as allowing data mining.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] With respect to software, the term *interoperability* is used to describe the capability of different programs to exchange data via a common set of exchange formats, to read and write the same file formats, and to use the same communication protocols.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The lack of interoperability can be a consequence of a lack of attention to standardization during the design of a program.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Indeed, interoperability is not taken for granted in the non-standards-based portion of the computing world.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Standards-developing organizations provide open public software specifications to facilitate interoperability; examples include the Oasis-Open organization and buildingSMART (formerly the International Alliance for Interoperability).
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Another example of a neutral party is the RFC documents from the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF).
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The Open Service for Lifecycle Collaboration community is working on finding a common standard in order that software tools can share and exchange data e.g., bugs, tasks, requirements etc.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The final goal is to agree on an open standard for interoperability of open source application lifecycle management tools.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Java is an example of an interoperable programming language that allows for programs to be written once and run anywhere with a Java virtual machine.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] A program in Java, so long as it does not use system-specific functionality, will maintain interoperability with all systems that have a Java virtual machine available.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Applications will maintain compatibility because, while the implementation is different, the underlying language interfaces are the same.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Product engineering Implements the common standard, or a sub-profile thereof, as defined by the industry and community partnerships with the specific intention of achieving interoperability with other software implementations, also following the same standard or sub-profile thereof.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Industry and community partnership Industry and community partnerships, either domestic or international, sponsor standard workgroups with the purpose of defining a common standard that may be used to allow software systems to intercommunicate for a defined purpose.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] At times, an industry or community will sub-profile an existing standard produced by another organization to reduce options and thus make interoperability more achievable for implementations.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] This technique has some of the same technical results as using a common vendor product to produce interoperability.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The common technology can come through third-party libraries or open-source developments.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Standard implementation Software interoperability requires a common agreement that is normally arrived at via an industrial, national or international standard.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Each of these has an important role in reducing variability in intercommunication software and enhancing a common understanding of the end goal to be achieved.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Language interoperability is the capability of two different programming languages to natively interact as part of the same system and operate on the same kind of data structures.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] There are many ways programming languages are interoperable with one another.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] HTML, CSS, and JavaScript are interoperable as they are used in tandem in webpages.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Some object oriented languages are interoperable thanks to their shared hosting virtual machine (e.g. .NET CLI compliant languages in the Common Language Runtime and JVM compliant languages in the Java Virtual Machine).
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Unified interoperability is the property of a system that allows for the integration of real-time and non-real time communications, activities, data, and information services (i.e., unified) and the display and coordination of those services across systems and devices (i.e., interoperability).
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Unified interoperability provides the capability to communicate and exchange processing across different applications, data, and infrastructure.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Interoperability tends to be regarded as an issue for experts and its implications for daily living are sometimes underrated.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The European Union Microsoft competition case shows how interoperability concerns important questions of power relationships.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] In 2004, the European Commission found that Microsoft had abused its market power by deliberately restricting interoperability between Windows Workgroup servers and non-Microsoft work group servers.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] By doing so, Microsoft was able to protect its dominant market position for work group server operating systems, the heart of corporate IT networks.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Microsoft was ordered to disclose complete and accurate interface documentation, which could enable rival vendors to compete on an equal footing (*the interoperability remedy*).
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Interoperability has also surfaced in the software patent debate in the European Parliament (June–July 2005).
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Interoperability is often more of an organizational issue.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Interoperability can have a significant impact on the organizations concerned, raising issues of ownership (do people want to share their data? or are they dealing with information silos?), labor relations (are people prepared to undergo training?) and usability.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] In this context, a more apt definition is captured in the term *business process interoperability*.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Interoperability can have important economic consequences; for example, research has estimated the cost of inadequate interoperability in the US capital facilities industry to be $15.8 billion a year.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] If competitors' products are not interoperable (due to causes such as patents, trade secrets or coordination failures), the result may well be monopoly or market failure.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] For this reason, it may be prudent for user communities or governments to take steps to encourage interoperability in various situations.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] At least 30 international bodies and countries have implemented eGovernment-based interoperability framework initiatives called e-GIF, while in the US, there is the NIEM initiative.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The need for *plug-and-play* interoperability – the ability to take a medical device out of its box and easily make it work with one's other devices – has attracted great attention from both healthcare providers and industry.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Increasingly, medical devices like incubators and imaging systems feature software that integrates at the point of care and with electronic systems, such as electronic medical records.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] At the 2016 Regulatory Affairs Professionals Society (RAPS) meeting, experts in the field like Angela N.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Johnson with GE Healthcare and Jeff Shuren of the United States Food and Drug Administration, provided practical seminars on how companies developing new medical devices, and hospitals installing them, can work more effectively to align interoperable software systems.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Railways have greater or lesser interoperability depending on conforming to standards of gauge, couplings, brakes, signalling, loading gauge, and structure gauge to mention a few parameters.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] For passenger rail service, different railway platform height and width clearance standards may also affect interoperability.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] North American freight and intercity passenger railroads are highly interoperable, but systems in Europe, Asia, Africa, Central and South America, and Australia are much less so.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The parameter most difficult to overcome (at reasonable cost) is incompatibility of gauge, though variable gauge axle systems can be used on rolling stock.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The condition achieved among communications-electronics systems or items of communications-electronics equipment when information or services can be exchanged directly and satisfactorily between them or their users.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The degree of interoperability should be defined when referring to specific cases.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Many organizations are dedicated to interoperability.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Some concentrate on eGovernment, eBusiness or data exchange in general.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] Internationally, Network Centric Operations Industry Consortium facilitates global interoperability across borders, language and technical barriers.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] In the built environment, the International Alliance for Interoperability started in 1994 and was renamed buildingSMART in 2005.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] In Europe, the European Commission and its IDABC program issue the European Interoperability Framework.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] IDABC was succeeded by the Interoperability Solutions for European Public Administrations (ISA) program.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] They also initiated the Semantic Interoperability Centre Europe (SEMIC.EU).
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] A European Land Information Service (EULIS) was established in 2006, as a consortium of European National Land Registers.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The aim of the service is to establish a single portal through which customers are provided with access to information about individual properties, about land and property registration services, and about the associated legal environment.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The European Interoperability Framework (EIF) considered four kinds of interoperability: legal interoperability, organizational interoperability, semantic interoperability, and technical interoperability.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] In the European Research Cluster on the Internet of Things (IERC) and IoT Semantic Interoperability Best Practices; four kinds of interoperability are distinguished: syntactical interoperability, technical interoperability, semantic interoperability, and organizational interoperability.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] In the United States, the General Services Administration Component Organization and Registration Environment (CORE.GOV) initiative provided a collaboration environment for component development, sharing, registration, and reuse in the early 2000s.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] A related initiative is the ongoing National Information Exchange Model (NIEM) work and component repository.
[src:fhir-health/interoperability] The National Institute of Standards and Technology serves as an agency for measurement standards.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] The openEHR specifications are maintained by the openEHR Foundation, a not for profit foundation supporting the open research, development, and implementation of openEHR EHRs.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] The specifications are based on a combination of 15 years of European and Australian research and development into EHRs and new paradigms, including what has become known as the archetype methodology for specification of content.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] The openEHR specifications include information and service models for the EHR, demographics, clinical workflow and archetypes.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] They are designed to be the basis of a medico-legally sound, distributed, versioned EHR infrastructure.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] The use of the first two enable the development of 'archetypes' and 'templates', which are formal models of clinical and related content, and constitute a layer of *de facto* standards of their own, far more numerous than the base specifications on which they are built.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] The query language enables queries to be built based on the archetypes, rather than physical database schemata, thus decoupling queries from physical persistence details.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] The service models define access to key back-end services, including the EHR Service and Demographics Service, while a growing set of lightweight REST-based APIs based on archetype paths are used for application access.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] The openEHR Architecture Overview provides a summary of the architecture and the detailed specifications.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] A central part of the openEHR specifications is the set of information models, known in openEHR as 'reference models'.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] The models constitute the base information models for openEHR systems, and define the invariant semantics of the Electronic Health Record (EHR), EHR Extract, and Demographics model, as well as supporting data types, data structures, identifiers and useful design patterns.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] This is justified by the need to deal scalably with the generic problem in health of a very large, growing, and ever-changing set of information types.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] Clinical content is specified in terms of two types of artefact which exist outside the information model.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] The first, known as "archetypes" provides a place to formally define re-usable data point and data group definitions, i.e. content items that will be re-used in numerous contexts.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] Typical examples include "systemic arterial blood pressure measurement" and "serum sodium".
[src:fhir-health/openehr] Many such data points occur in logical groups, e.g. the group of data items to document an allergic reaction, or the analytes in a liver function test result.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] Some archetypes contain numerous data points, e.g.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] 50, although a more common number is 10–20.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] A collection of archetypes can be understood as a "library" of re-usable domain content definitions, with each archetype functioning as a "governance unit", whose contents are co-designed, reviewed and published.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] The second kind of artefact is known in openEHR as a "template", and is used to logically represent a use case-specific data-set, such as the data items making up a patient discharge summary, or a radiology report.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] A template is constructed by referencing relevant items from a number of archetypes.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] A template might only require one or two data points or groups from each archetype.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] In terms of the technical representation, openEHR templates cannot violate the semantics of the archetypes from which they are constructed.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] Templates are almost always developed for local use by software developers and clinical analysts.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] Templates are typically defined for GUI screen forms, message definitions and document definitions, and as such, correspond to "operational" content definitions.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] This provides a basis for standardised querying to work.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] Without the archetype "library" level, every data set (i.e. chunk of operational content) is uniquely defined and a standard approach to querying is difficult.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] Accordingly, openEHR defines a method of querying based on archetypes, known as AQL (Archetype Querying Language).
[src:fhir-health/openehr] Notably, openEHR has been used to model shared care plan.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] The archetypes have been designed to accommodate the concepts of the shared care plan.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] While individual health records may be vastly different in content, the core information in openEHR data instances always complies to archetypes.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] The way this works is by creating archetypes which express clinical information in a way that is highly reusable, even universal in some cases.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] openEHR archetypes are expressed in "Archetype Definition Language", an openEHR public specification.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] Two versions are available: ADL 1.4, and ADL 2, a new release with better support for specialisation, redefinition and annotations, among other improvements.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] The 1.4 release of ADL and its "object model" counterpart Archetype Object Model (AOM) are the basis for the CEN and ISO "Archetype Definition Language" standard (ISO standard 13606-2).
[src:fhir-health/openehr] Templates have historically been developed in a simple, de facto industry-developed XML format, known as ".oet", after the file extension.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] ADL 2 defines a way to express templates seamlessly with archetypes, using extensions of the ADL language.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] Various principles for developing archetypes have been identified.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] For example, a set of openEHR archetypes needs to be quality managed to conform to a number of axioms such as being mutually exclusive.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] The archetypes can be managed independently from software implementations and infrastructure, in the hands of clinician groups to ensure they meet the real needs on the ground.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] Archetypes are designed to allow the specification of clinical knowledge to evolve and develop over time.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] Challenges in implementation of information designs expressed in openEHR centre on the extent to which actual system constraints are in harmony with the information design.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] In the field of Electronic health records there are a number of existing information models with overlaps in their scope which are difficult to manage, such as between HL7 V3 and SNOMED CT.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] The openEHR approach faces harmonisation challenges unless used in isolation.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] Following the openEHR approach, the use of shared and governed archetypes globally would ensure openEHR health data could be consistently manipulated and viewed, regardless of the technical, organisational and cultural context.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] This approach also means the actual data models used by any EHR are flexible, given that new archetypes may be defined to meet future needs of clinical record keeping.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] Recently, work in Australia has demonstrated how archetypes and templates may be used to facilitate the use of legacy health record and message data in an openEHR health record system, and output standardised messages and CDA documents.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] The openEHR framework is consistent with the Electronic Health Record Communication Standard (ISO 13606), and the Archetype Object Model 2 (AOM2) has been officially accepted by ISO TC 215 as the draft specification for the 2017 revision of ISO 13606:2.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] openEHR archetypes are being used by the National e-Health Transition Authority of Australia, the UK NHS Health and Social Care Information Centre (HSCIC), the Norwegian Nasjonal IKT organisation, the Catalan Health Service (CatSalut) and the Slovenian Ministry of Health.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] openEHR has been selected as the basis for the standardised EHR in Brazil.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] It is beginning to be utilised in commercial solutions throughout the world, including those produced by the openEHR Industry Partners.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] One of the outcomes of openEHR modelling approach is the open development of archetypes, templates and terminology subsets to represent health data.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] Due to the open nature of openEHR, these structures are publicly available to be used and implemented in health information systems.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] Community users are able to share, discuss and approve these structures in a collaborative repository known as the Clinical Knowledge Manager (CKM), developed by Ocean Informatics Pty Ltd.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] The UK CKM, maintained by Apperta has been suspended since 1st of November 2024.
[src:fhir-health/openehr] The clinical models can be accessed via their GitHub repository.
